sec.p:
Bonds of similar maturities have similar yields. Therefore, if the eligible bonds belong to a convenient range of maturities, their yields will be similar. In this case,(21)will be small, and delivering a bond different from the CTD will generate only a small loss. This was precisely the metric proposed inSection IIto judge alternative forms
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $g( \cdot ,\,\cdot ) $ \end{document}
               for the futures invoice price function(1); hence the rationale of the TNBS.

Now I compare the TNBS with the CFS. Let us say that a futures invoice price determination systemworks perfectlywhen, for allX,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{Profit}\,( X) =0$ \end{document}
               . (This is consistent withSec. II.) Assume that the yield curve isflat. While the CFS works perfectly only when the level of the yield is equal to the 6% reference rate, the TNBS works perfectly foranylevel of yield by(21). Thus the world in which the CFS works perfectly is much more implausible than the one in which the TNBS does. It is somewhat ironic that the CFS works perfectly only in a world in which the yields are fixed, in which case a bond futures contract would be useless. The empirical part of this paper shows that the proposed system is superior to the CFS also for real‐world nonflat yield curves.

CBOT (2000) considers a frequently asked question: How do you determine the yield of a Treasury futures contract on the basis of its price? This paper concludes that, in the CFS, futures contracts do not have a yield.17In contrast, in the TNBS there is a clear yield, namely, the yield of the NB. This yield can be compared to the yields of Treasury bonds, knowing that, at expiration,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $y^{\mathrm{NB}\,}_{T}$ \end{document}
               will equal the highest among the yields of all eligible bonds. This feature adds to the contract’s appeal to speculators and the public in general.

